<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-pos-migration-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why this is forced</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Why QuickBooks Desktop POS users need to migrate</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>QuickBooks Desktop Point of Sale is the in-store register and inventory software Intuit sold to ring up sales, track stock, and manage customers, with a link back to QuickBooks for the accounting. <strong>Intuit discontinued it.</strong> Intuit stopped selling the product and ended support, and the platform reached end of life &mdash; Intuit announced a transition and partnered to move users to an alternative point-of-sale system, such as Shopify POS. There is no &ldquo;keep using it as-is forever&rdquo; path: once a discontinued product is past end of life, it stops getting security patches, payment-processing support, and help, which is why every Desktop POS user has to move to a new POS.</p>
      <p>The move isn&rsquo;t only a new register. Your store data &mdash; the item list, customer records, sales history, and on-hand inventory counts &mdash; lives in Desktop POS today, and it has to be exported and carried into the replacement system, then the replacement has to be connected to your accounting so sales and fees keep landing in the books. The pieces that go wrong are predictable: historical sales that don&rsquo;t come across, inventory counts that don&rsquo;t reconcile to what&rsquo;s on the shelf, and sales, refunds, and processor fees that map to the wrong accounts so the books no longer tie. That accounting-side work &mdash; planning the export, setting up QuickBooks Online, connecting the new POS, and reconciling &mdash; is what an independent ProAdvisor firm does. Which POS hardware and software you adopt is between you and that vendor; we&rsquo;re not the POS vendor.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

